social_posts.post_text:
So I went on an Instagram cleanse. 29 days! Since I haven’t been on Twitter or FB for about three years, this meant basically living in a cave for the last month. I am not sure how to feel about it. 

One the one hand, for my writing, it was great. I finished a draft of a novel (first time since the pandemic, MAN it took awhile) and started another one. Not sure if anyone will ever see them, but at least it is something. I worked whenever I wasn’t driving my kid places, which is pretty much my actual job these days. I have memories of book signings and conferences and writer friends, but they are fading. Being off all socials does that, too. Like I forget I had any books before these ones I’m trying to finish now. 

Upshot: I  missed being connected. I have a LOT of friends with super cute babies right now. And it’s harder, these days, to just text someone and ask what’s going on. My friend circle is so small it’s pretty much a square. So now, I am going to try and find a balance, so I am not so very sad and lonely but also still able to work and be productive. Do you have a system that works? Want to share it? I’m all ears. 🙏

I took the picture above driving home the other night. The sunset was so amazing. This shot doesn’t even begin to do it justice. But I snapped one anyway. Every time I look at it I remember the difference. Because there is one. 

Sending love and peace to all as December begins. ❤️

The hand out the window made me cry the first time I saw it. Still gets me! I have no idea why. Maybe it’s just the power of beginnings? 

(Yes, I am watching it *again*. It’s been a week! )

The *idea* was to get a nice family sunset beach picture. Maybe for a holiday card? Instead, I tripped over a dune and face planted moments before this shot was taken. So here we all are, laughing at me. I feel like it says everything about this year. Happy holidays! Here’s to peace in 2023. ❤️ (Thank you to my family for approving this picture, I promise I am done now. )

Writers: how many books have you attempted since March 2020? Personally, I’m at two and a half. The first one was a bit of a mess (but I stickered my draft very nicely). The second one has my HEART but I had to set it aside for now (although I can’t stop thinking about it). And the third is the rock I am pushing up my own hill of anxiety every day. I don’t even know why I’m posting this as it *looks* like I am not particularly good at my job right now. But writing is messy under the best of circumstances and the last couple of years have been a doozy. All you can do it keep going, page by page. If you’re struggling too, whether it be with words or life in general, hang in. We’ll get there. ⭐️💗🌸
Flashback to writing retreats I was SO lucky to attend in February of 2016 and 2018. Grateful for all these amazing ladies! I miss y’all. ❤️

For me, writing is always a matter of working and then rewards. Lately I’ve gotten super into miniatures and the dollhouse where all my stories began. I finish my work for the day and then sit in front of it and move things around the way it is hard to do with chapters and plot lines. I special ordered these from @kayteekays.minis so my tiny library would have all my titles. I cannot explain why this makes me so happy! It just does. #amwriting #whateverittakes
Part Ted Lasso. Part my optimism that I worry may in fact be denial. But I’m going to keep this my message until I get where I want to be. Wherever that is. ⭐️ #amwriting

I have spent *entirely* too much time today studying this spreadsheet of my books, characters and places, which I first saw via @hatespinnerbaitpod. It’s the coolest and not just because my memory is so bad lately I’m starting to worry I am the only one keeping track of all this. Also as an author it is insanely flattering to think anyone took this much time and effort thinking about your work. Wow. 

 I honestly started making all the connections in Lakeview because I live in my hometown. I don’t know what it’s like NOT to bump into my middle school crush at the gas station and have to hide. For the books, though, I was more interested in the bigger idea that we are all connected somehow, even if we don’t always realize it. It feels more important than ever after the last three years, which have felt isolating to say the least. I can’t WAIT to get out and see my readers again. Hey, maybe next tour I’ll do a quiz with prizes? I will have to start studying now. Or as soon as I finish this book I’m writing. Stay tuned!

Today is my birthday. It’s been a year! Actually, if I am honest, the last three have taught me so much. The highest highs and truly some lows I wasn’t sure I’d endure. So grateful to everyone who has sent a comment or thumbs up along the way. Man, have I learned a lot. Here’s to summer, y’all. ☀️☀️☀️ (yes, I am currently obsessed with miniatures.)

It’s that time of year when it seems everyone is off doing something awesome. Don’t get me wrong: I LOVE seeing my friends happy. But there are times, on a Sunday morning, when you realize your own life is drastically dull. Like, basically watching the hummingbirds and 90 Day Fiancé The Other Way while drinking hot water because you’re too anxious for much caffeine dull . At the same time, things are NUTS: end of school, beginning of camp, endless forms (driving school? What?). This weird balance of rushing and stillness, I have learned, is what my life looks like being lived. Just watch the hummingbirds circle, rest and scuffIe. They know. 🙌🏻🦜

Is it summer without a @sdessen romance? See you in Colby 😍

It's our last night at the lake tonight. Every year, I look forward to these handful of days so much, full of laughter and music and stories. This has been a year of so much change, but thankfully---and I am so thankful!---some things do stay the same. Today the ice cream truck came and I made a cardboard dollhouse with some of the most imaginative kids ever. And the summer is only just starting! Here's to days ahead of peace and fun (remember those?) for everyone. It's like the beginning of a novel. Who knows what can happen?
Goodnight and sleep well

Since The Rest of The Story was published in 2019, I have written over a thousand pages of fiction. None of it has hit just right, so I’m about to start something new. But before then, I’m going to post a few glimpses, just to honor all those hundreds of hours I spent writing in the school parking lot, coffee shops and my couch. This was the prologue I wrote for the first one. I called it Grace Louise. As always, thanks for reading. 💗

Even as a kid, my cousin Noah was big. In size, yes. It was what you noticed first. Then: his huge heart, soul and spirit.  He was one of the kindest, most forgiving people I was ever lucky enough to know. Also: he had great taste in soulmates, and helped create three of my favorite humans. We all loved him so, so much. The only thing we couldn’t give him was time. 💔

Rest well, Cousin. I know you are in a place not so far away, maybe on the Cape, surrounded by family, music, gardens and laughter. We’ll see you there.

Some of you might remember way back when I had a blog on Livejournal. I did it for years, first a few times a week, then only on Fridays. I stopped for various reasons, but mostly because I was on Twitter all the time. Then I screwed up ROYALLY on that platform—almost four years ago, but who’s counting—and gave up all social media to reset and be better. This summer, though, I decided to start up again over on Substack, and it’s been so fun. Every week, I throw this thing out there. I probably repeat myself and there are way too many miniatures. But if you want to check it out, the link is in my bio. Have a good weekend, everyone!

I have been struggling the last week or so, just feeling The Sadness. You know it, maybe. When you’re tired and weepy and nothing seems like it will ever again work out. Therapy helps. Meds, too. Even so, sometimes I go down for the count. But! It does pass. Today was the first day I’ve felt like doing anything so I did this. What does it mean? I don’t know. But I do feel better. If you’re struggling, I hope you will too. Soon. ❤️
